1
00:00:04,040 --> 00:00:08,034
In this lecture we will see how radiation interacts

2
00:00:08,034 --> 00:00:10,830
with the interstellar and
intergalactic matter.

3
00:00:10,830 --> 00:00:13,681
Interactions occur at
all spatial scales

4
00:00:13,681 --> 00:00:17,146
and are analysed thanks to images and spectra

5
00:00:17,146 --> 00:00:22,198
giving constraints on the physical conditions 
of the gas and dust in cosmic clouds.

6
00:00:22,198 --> 00:00:25,840
The interstellar gas, apart from
the primordial hydrogen and helium 

7
00:00:25,840 --> 00:00:28,513
formed a few moments after
the Big Bang, is created by

8
00:00:28,523 --> 00:00:32,875
successive generations of stars
and is ejected 

9
00:00:32,875 --> 00:00:35,520
into the interstellar medium
after the death of

10
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:37,382
high- or low-mass stars. 

11
00:00:37,382 --> 00:00:39,889
For low mass stars,

12
00:00:39,889 --> 00:00:43,133
i.e. less massive than 8 solar masses,
planetary nebulae are formed, 

13
00:00:43,720 --> 00:00:46,092
while for the stars with masses

14
00:00:46,092 --> 00:00:49,490
exceeding 8 solar masses,
a supernova explosion occurs

15
00:00:49,490 --> 00:00:53,235
leaving spectacular filaments
as shown in the figure.

16
00:00:53,483 --> 00:00:56,880
This image shows the Crab nebula,
Messier 1

17
00:00:56,898 --> 00:00:59,725
that is a result of the supernova 
explosion visible

18
00:00:59,725 --> 00:01:02,552
even to the naked eye in 1054.

19
00:01:02,552 --> 00:01:05,381
Then, the gas is recycled
into the interstellar medium,

20
00:01:05,381 --> 00:01:07,760
in a galaxy like this one, 
Messier 51,

21
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:10,879
where the hydrogen emission
is well visible in the red

22
00:01:10,879 --> 00:01:15,199
in the spiral arms of the galaxy.
The hydrogen emission

23
00:01:15,199 --> 00:01:20,267
is created by the ionised gas
excited by the swarm of

24
00:01:20,267 --> 00:01:22,996
young massive stars
visible in the blue

25
00:01:22,996 --> 00:01:24,925
in the arms of the galaxy .

26
00:01:25,475 --> 00:01:29,080
Apart from the gas in galaxies,

27
00:01:29,080 --> 00:01:32,274
there is also dust that absorbs

28
00:01:32,274 --> 00:01:34,890
background radiation.
This effect can be seen here

29
00:01:34,890 --> 00:01:38,519
in the form of dark trails
through the arms of the galaxy.

30
00:01:38,682 --> 00:01:41,945
The background light is absorbed
by dust.

31
00:01:41,945 --> 00:01:45,959
From this mix of gas and 
dust, new generations

32
00:01:45,959 --> 00:01:50,730
of stars, possibly with associated 
planetary systems are formed.

33
00:01:50,730 --> 00:01:53,436
Let's see in details what is 
happening in a nebula.

34
00:01:53,570 --> 00:01:59,034
The Carina nebula shown here
at optical wavelengths.

35
00:01:59,034 --> 00:02:02,761
Some sources of ionisation can
easily be identified,

36
00:02:02,761 --> 00:02:06,170
like in this place - a small stellar cluster

37
00:02:06,210 --> 00:02:08,350
certainly composed of young 
hot stars.

38
00:02:08,350 --> 00:02:12,510
Another stellar cluster 
can be seen here. 

39
00:02:13,247 --> 00:02:16,916
Those stars ionize the surrounding gas. 

40
00:02:17,086 --> 00:02:20,236
The gas divides into 
protons and electrons.

41
00:02:20,575 --> 00:02:24,760
Possibly, they will recombine,
electrons fall back into

42
00:02:24,760 --> 00:02:29,308
the lower energy level
while at the same time emitting photons

43
00:02:29,308 --> 00:02:31,816
with a range of wavelengths.

44
00:02:31,816 --> 00:02:35,738
Each colour indicates a different 
emission line,

45
00:02:35,738 --> 00:02:37,819
as it was shown in previous
chapters.

46
00:02:38,446 --> 00:02:43,440
The density of the gas

47
00:02:43,733 --> 00:02:47,623
is very low,

48
00:02:47,753 --> 00:02:51,525
roughly one gas particle
per cm³,

49
00:02:51,525 --> 00:02:58,495
which gives 
ρ = 10^-21 kg/m³.

50
00:02:58,495 --> 00:03:00,489
There can be great differences 
in the densities

51
00:03:00,489 --> 00:03:03,040
from one nebula to the other,
from one galaxy to the other.

52
00:03:03,124 --> 00:03:05,760
This density corresponds to
the ionised gas that often produces

53
00:03:05,760 --> 00:03:08,459
emission lines. We find also dusty regions,

54
00:03:08,459 --> 00:03:11,429
similar to those shown before
in the spiral galaxy.

55
00:03:11,429 --> 00:03:13,883
Dust absorbs radiation.

56
00:03:13,883 --> 00:03:17,092
In fact, this whole region

57
00:03:17,092 --> 00:03:20,336
is affected by dust absorption.

58
00:03:20,336 --> 00:03:23,765
Mass densities in this kind of
regions are even lower,

59
00:03:23,765 --> 00:03:29,316
about 10 ^-13 particles per cm³

60
00:03:29,316 --> 00:03:32,094
which is 10 ^ 13 times smaller
than the gas density.

61
00:03:32,094 --> 00:03:34,314
On the other hand, dust particles
are much heavier

62
00:03:34,314 --> 00:03:37,761
because the dust is composed of atoms and molecules.

63
00:03:38,076 --> 00:03:45,652
The mass density is of the order of 
10^ -23 kg/m³.

64
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:50,046
This means that there is 13 orders of magnitude
less dust particles than in the gas, 

65
00:03:50,046 --> 00:03:52,223
but in mass density

66
00:03:52,223 --> 00:03:56,596
dust is only 100 times less massive 
per unit volume than gas.

67
00:03:57,234 --> 00:04:00,115
All we said previously was about
gas and dust in nebulae,

68
00:04:00,115 --> 00:04:02,026
Let's now have a closer look at 
the Milky Way.

69
00:04:02,026 --> 00:04:03,743
So objects with much larger spatial scales,

70
00:04:03,743 --> 00:04:08,852
from this place to this other one in the slide
the distance is about 5 kiloparsec.

71
00:04:08,871 --> 00:04:10,648
On the previous slide 

72
00:04:10,648 --> 00:04:13,187
the scale was about tens of parsec.

73
00:04:13,187 --> 00:04:15,493
Here, the scale corresponds to
the kiloparsec scale.

74
00:04:15,493 --> 00:04:17,933
The nebula that was shown 
just before

75
00:04:17,933 --> 00:04:20,355
has roughly this size,

76
00:04:20,355 --> 00:04:22,913
quite small comparing to
the Milky Way.

77
00:04:22,913 --> 00:04:27,009
On the other hand, dust extends
over a large region,

78
00:04:27,009 --> 00:04:32,523
those areas correspond 
to dusty spots

79
00:04:32,523 --> 00:04:38,927
that absorb the light coming
from the stars situated behind.

80
00:04:38,927 --> 00:04:42,440
Here are other dust regions.

81
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:45,720
In conclusion, the dust and the gas
intervene at all scales.

82
00:04:45,720 --> 00:04:49,643
Let's take a look at what is 
happening with the ionised gas

83
00:04:49,643 --> 00:04:51,368
that recombines

84
00:04:51,368 --> 00:04:53,996
and emits radiation

85
00:04:53,996 --> 00:04:55,763
creating something we can observe

86
00:04:55,763 --> 00:04:57,363
nebulae.

87
00:04:57,363 --> 00:04:58,889
Here we will assume 

88
00:04:58,889 --> 00:05:02,647
a gaseous nebula

89
00:05:02,647 --> 00:05:05,420
composed of hydrogen,
so as to simplify the calculations.

90
00:05:05,420 --> 00:05:07,855
Of course, the composition
could well be different

91
00:05:07,855 --> 00:05:09,111
in this kind of cloud.

92
00:05:09,111 --> 00:05:11,790
Then, here is a ionizing
source: stars.

93
00:05:11,790 --> 00:05:16,127
This ionizing source splits 
the atoms, of hydrogen in this case,

94
00:05:16,127 --> 00:05:17,320
into protons and electrons.

95
00:05:17,320 --> 00:05:19,696
They do not stay in 
this state,

96
00:05:19,696 --> 00:05:22,920
they will tend to recombine
and emit light.

97
00:05:22,920 --> 00:05:24,600
Now, we will try to estimate 

98
00:05:24,600 --> 00:05:28,160
the typical radius of a nebula

99
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:31,231
that is the Strömgren radius,

100
00:05:31,231 --> 00:05:34,060
after the astronomer who 
calculated it for the first time.

101
00:05:34,060 --> 00:05:36,440
What we will try to 
characterise is 

102
00:05:36,440 --> 00:05:40,352
this limiting radius
of the nebula,

103
00:05:40,352 --> 00:05:42,037
the Strömgren radius.

104
00:05:42,346 --> 00:05:46,131
As always in science,
there is an equilibrium. 

105
00:05:46,131 --> 00:05:49,693
There are ionising photons 
coming from the source,

106
00:05:49,693 --> 00:05:51,389
from the centre of the nebula.

107
00:05:51,389 --> 00:05:54,679
Then, there are electrons
that recombine with the protons

108
00:05:54,679 --> 00:05:57,521
that were inonized by the
radiation field. 

109
00:05:57,521 --> 00:06:01,179
The flux of
ionizing photons

110
00:06:01,179 --> 00:06:05,821
is equal to the 
recombination ratio

111
00:06:05,821 --> 00:06:07,759
of the proton-electron pairs. 

112
00:06:07,789 --> 00:06:12,772
The number of recombinations
is equal to the volume of the nebula:

113
00:06:12,772 --> 00:06:18,186
4/3 pi x r^3

114
00:06:18,186 --> 00:06:22,167
times the number of available 
proton-electron pairs,

115
00:06:22,167 --> 00:06:27,264
that is  <i>ne</i> for electrons
and <i>nh</i> for protons.

116
00:06:27,264 --> 00:06:29,725
In this equation,
there is also a constant 

117
00:06:29,725 --> 00:06:32,043
that comes from quantum mechanics,

118
00:06:32,043 --> 00:06:34,040
and the origins of which 
is not needed to be known here.

119
00:06:34,040 --> 00:06:37,024
It is just a physical constant

120
00:06:37,024 --> 00:06:46,235
that is equal to about 3 x 10 ^-13 cm^3*s^-1

121
00:06:46,235 --> 00:06:51,761
for a gas of with temperature around 8000K

122
00:06:51,761 --> 00:06:54,914
which is a typical temperature for 
diffuse nebulae. 

123
00:06:55,054 --> 00:06:59,315
We have calculated 
the recombination ratio

124
00:06:59,315 --> 00:07:01,491
as a function of radius - the parameter
that we are interested in, 

125
00:07:01,491 --> 00:07:04,870
and the electron and proton
density in the nebula.

126
00:07:04,870 --> 00:07:10,608
Now, let's calculate the number
of ionizing photons.

127
00:07:10,608 --> 00:07:15,839
For the calculations we take 
a hot star

128
00:07:15,839 --> 00:07:20,687
as a ionizing source

129
00:07:20,687 --> 00:07:26,047
with the temperature of about 45000K.

130
00:07:26,047 --> 00:07:29,488
This star has a
black body spectrum

131
00:07:29,488 --> 00:07:32,580
with its luminosity peak in the ultraviolet.

132
00:07:32,580 --> 00:07:38,195
According to the Wien law,  λmax
is equal to 640 Å

133
00:07:38,465 --> 00:07:40,785
which is in the ultraviolet part
of the spectrum

134
00:07:40,785 --> 00:07:43,471
where the photons carry
a lot of energy

135
00:07:43,471 --> 00:07:46,082
and so they can easily ionize matter.

136
00:07:46,082 --> 00:07:51,154
Here we have a nebula
composed of ionised hydrogen.

137
00:07:51,154 --> 00:07:54,421
Before the calculations, 
lets recall a bit of nomenclature.

138
00:07:54,421 --> 00:07:56,039
We have talked a lot 
about hydrogen,

139
00:07:56,039 --> 00:07:58,884
so lets now present
some notations.

140
00:07:58,884 --> 00:08:01,995
It may be that you
are familiar with it,

141
00:08:01,995 --> 00:08:03,680
so treat it as a reminder.

142
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:07,333
If you have such a notation: 1H

143
00:08:07,333 --> 00:08:09,916
it stands for an hydrogen nucleus.

144
00:08:10,234 --> 00:08:13,083
A notation 2H

145
00:08:13,083 --> 00:08:15,454
stands for a deuterium nucleus.

146
00:08:15,454 --> 00:08:18,696
In this case there is one extra 
neutron in the nucleus.

147
00:08:18,696 --> 00:08:21,733
Lets move on to atoms, so
we have now also an electron,

148
00:08:21,733 --> 00:08:25,955
that we note as HI.

149
00:08:25,955 --> 00:08:28,361
this is an atom of neutral hydrogen.

150
00:08:28,361 --> 00:08:33,272
The electron in this atom 
is in its lowest possible energy state

151
00:08:33,272 --> 00:08:36,075
with -13.6 eV.

152
00:08:36,075 --> 00:08:40,278
It means that in order to ionise an hydrogen
atom, 13.6 eV must be delivered.

153
00:08:40,278 --> 00:08:47,627
In this case, one notes HII
for the ionized hydrogen.

154
00:08:47,657 --> 00:08:56,960
Earlier, a notation 
Hα, Hβ, Hγ, etc. was shown. 

155
00:08:56,960 --> 00:08:58,844
Pay attention not to confuse it
with the notation that  was shown before.

156
00:08:58,844 --> 00:09:02,111
Those are the hydrogen
emission lines.

157
00:09:02,111 --> 00:09:08,421
We can also write H2 which indicates

158
00:09:08,421 --> 00:09:10,962
that two hydrogen atoms now form a molecule.

159
00:09:10,962 --> 00:09:12,702
So, beware of all the different notations.

160
00:09:12,702 --> 00:09:16,560
That is all for the hydrogen nebula.

161
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:20,331
Now, let's recall that we 
consider a single star

162
00:09:20,331 --> 00:09:23,189
with 45000K in the 
centre of the nebula.

163
00:09:23,189 --> 00:09:26,600
The radiation peak is at 640 Å. 

164
00:09:26,600 --> 00:09:31,767
And, assuming that most photons belong to
that peak,

165
00:09:31,767 --> 00:09:37,822
each photon has about
the energy Eγ = hν

166
00:09:37,822 --> 00:09:40,930
Then, let us imagine that all photons are indeed
emitted at the peak,

167
00:09:40,930 --> 00:09:43,478
Thus, all photons have precisely
that energy:

168
00:09:43,478 --> 00:09:48,152
The total amounts to 1,54 10^-5 J

169
00:09:48,152 --> 00:09:51,604
which corresponds to 19 eV.

170
00:09:51,604 --> 00:09:55,714
Obviously, those are photons
with an energy higher than

171
00:09:55,714 --> 00:10:01,015
 the ionisation energy: 13.6eV.

172
00:10:01,015 --> 00:10:04,888
It means that if a star 

173
00:10:04,888 --> 00:10:08,761
surrounded by hydrogen
is considered,

174
00:10:08,761 --> 00:10:12,636
then, with a good approximation,
all the hydrogen in the nebula is ionized.

175
00:10:12,636 --> 00:10:18,149
because of the photon flux
carrying an energy higher

176
00:10:18,149 --> 00:10:21,074
than the hydrogen ionization energy.

177
00:10:22,731 --> 00:10:27,086
Now, we assume that all 
the hydrogen is ionized and so

178
00:10:27,320 --> 00:10:29,321
ne = nH,

179
00:10:29,321 --> 00:10:32,212
and there is the same number 
of electrons than protons.

180
00:10:32,212 --> 00:10:35,444
This implies that the equation for 
the recombination ratio can be rewritten

181
00:10:35,444 --> 00:10:39,880
as a function

182
00:10:39,880 --> 00:10:43,579
of the hydrogen atom density,

183
00:10:43,579 --> 00:10:47,278
and it is equal to
the photon flux

184
00:10:47,278 --> 00:10:50,979
carrying an energy at least sufficient 
to ionize the atoms.

185
00:10:50,979 --> 00:10:54,168
Inverting this equation,

186
00:10:54,168 --> 00:10:57,474
we find the radius that is

187
00:10:57,474 --> 00:11:01,779
the limiting radius in the equilibrium,

188
00:11:01,779 --> 00:11:04,644
the  Strömgren radius.

189
00:11:04,644 --> 00:11:10,067
It will be equal to three times 
the number of ionizing photons

190
00:11:10,067 --> 00:11:15,840
over 4πα times nH²

191
00:11:15,840 --> 00:11:19,601
to the power 1/3.

192
00:11:19,601 --> 00:11:22,721
This is the equation for
the Strömgren radius.

193
00:11:22,721 --> 00:11:24,640
It is given as a function
of the following values:

194
00:11:24,640 --> 00:11:26,265
a physical constant,

195
00:11:26,265 --> 00:11:31,614
the density of the nebula
and the number of ionizing photons.

196
00:11:31,614 --> 00:11:35,327
The number of the ionizing 
photons can be estimated.

197
00:11:35,327 --> 00:11:39,268
In the easiest way, it is

198
00:11:39,268 --> 00:11:43,156
the stellar luminosity

199
00:11:43,156 --> 00:11:45,004
the stellar luminosity

200
00:11:45,004 --> 00:11:46,892
in the centre of the nebula

201
00:11:46,892 --> 00:11:49,513
divided by the photon energy.

202
00:11:49,513 --> 00:11:55,337
For a star with a
surface temperature

203
00:11:55,337 --> 00:12:00,520
T* = 45 000K

204
00:12:00,520 --> 00:12:11,227
the luminosity is equal to
1,3 x10^5  solar luminosity.

205
00:12:11,227 --> 00:12:13,420
This implies that the number
of ionizing photons

206
00:12:13,420 --> 00:12:22,441
is equal to 1,6 10^49 photons/s.

207
00:12:22,441 --> 00:12:27,920
This gives an estimate of 
the number of ionizing photons.

208
00:12:27,920 --> 00:12:30,752
Lets now estimate NH.

209
00:12:30,752 --> 00:12:37,044
For NH = 5000 / cm3

210
00:12:37,044 --> 00:12:41,080
the nebula is relatively dense,

211
00:12:41,080 --> 00:12:48,667
and the Stromgren radius 
is roughly equal to 0.3 parsec.

212
00:12:48,667 --> 00:12:51,335
This radius depends on the number
of stars in the nebula,

213
00:12:51,335 --> 00:12:59,666
but typically the Strömgren radius
is about 0.1 - 100 parsec

214
00:12:59,874 --> 00:13:01,907
for a typical nebula
in the Milky Way

215
00:13:02,101 --> 00:13:05,682
ionized by 

216
00:13:05,727 --> 00:13:08,274
a small stellar cluster.

217
00:13:08,274 --> 00:13:12,032
a small stellar cluster.

218
00:13:12,032 --> 00:13:15,448
This is the order of magnitude
of the size of ionized nebulae

219
00:13:15,448 --> 00:13:18,383
that can be found in the Milky Way,

220
00:13:18,383 --> 00:13:20,200
or in galaxies in general.

221
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:24,041
This is a wonderful example of a nebula
illustrating the Strömgren sphere - 

222
00:13:24,041 --> 00:13:29,423
NGC602 in the Small Magellanic Cloud
which is a satellite galaxy of our Galaxy.

223
00:13:29,423 --> 00:13:33,560
Here one can see a group
of blue stars

224
00:13:33,709 --> 00:13:37,237
in the centre of the nebula that ionizes
the gas as far as 50 parsec from the centre.

225
00:13:37,237 --> 00:13:41,268
This does not imply that
the nebula has its limit

226
00:13:41,268 --> 00:13:44,158
at 50 parsec and that there
is no gas further away.

227
00:13:44,158 --> 00:13:47,200
What it means is that the photon
flux produced

228
00:13:47,200 --> 00:13:52,356
by the stars in the centre of nebula
is not able to ionize the gas

229
00:13:52,356 --> 00:13:56,682
further away than the Strömgren radius.

230
00:13:56,682 --> 00:14:01,752
Now we will look closer 
at the dust absorption.

231
00:14:01,752 --> 00:14:04,680
Here you can see schematically 
represented some dust grains

232
00:14:04,680 --> 00:14:07,124
with sizes much larger than 
the atoms or molecules.

233
00:14:07,124 --> 00:14:10,457
It can be compared to the dust
that is on a table

234
00:14:10,457 --> 00:14:13,790
when one does not clean at his place,

235
00:14:13,790 --> 00:14:17,124
or to the chalk left on the blackboard,
for example.

236
00:14:17,124 --> 00:14:20,132
Let's take a volume element

237
00:14:20,132 --> 00:14:25,280
that is characterised by the length,

238
00:14:25,280 --> 00:14:28,922
input and output surfaces,

239
00:14:28,922 --> 00:14:32,183
and the density

240
00:14:32,183 --> 00:14:33,851
taken in a following way.

241
00:14:33,851 --> 00:14:39,620
This is the numerical density,
not the mass density,

242
00:14:39,620 --> 00:14:43,028
so it gives the number of dust grains
per unit volume.

243
00:14:43,028 --> 00:14:45,629
One can see clearly that
each dust grain

244
00:14:45,629 --> 00:14:50,312
obscures the light that
enters the volume element. 

245
00:14:50,312 --> 00:14:53,760
Each dust grain has a cross section

246
00:14:53,760 --> 00:14:58,280
that obscures a surface <i>dA</i>.

247
00:14:58,280 --> 00:15:01,088
This allows the determination
